	<item>
		<title>The Talk Show</title>
		<pubDate>Sat, 02 Aug 2025 09:20:00 +0900</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">42E703D6-B027-4065-812B-A393A759507D</guid>
		<link>https://lmnt.me/blog/the-talk-show.html</link>
		<dc:creator>Louie Mantia</dc:creator>
		<description><![CDATA[
			<p>On the latest episode of <a href="https://daringfireball.net/thetalkshow/2025/07/31/ep-428"><em>The Talk Show</em></a>, John and I talked for <strong>three hours</strong> about hoagies, light mode, dark mode, vintage MacOS, NeXT, Mac OS X, modern macOS, perceived stability, Aqua, and—of course—Liquid Glass.</p>
			<p>Leading up to this episode, I wrote these three posts about Liquid Glass, which you may be interested in:</p>
			<ul class="links">
				<li><a href="https://lmnt.me/blog/rose-gold-tinted-liquid-glasses.html">Rose-Gold-Tinted Liquid Glasses</a></li>
				<li><a href="https://lmnt.me/blog/ive-got-better-things-to-do-than-this-and-yet.html">I’ve Got Better Things To Do Than This, and Yet</a></li>
				<li><a href="https://lmnt.me/blog/a-responsibility-to-the-industry.html">A Responsibility to the Industry</a></li>
			</ul>
			<p>My issue with Liquid Glass is not an isolated one about the material quality and legibility, but rather a <strong>fundamental</strong> one about the implications of integrating buttons, tab bars, and text fields into content views. This issue is rooted in the directional change of Apple platforms from 2014.</p>
			<p>I know three-hour podcasts are often tedious. I can’t know if what we talk about will resonate with you or be worth your time.</p>
			<p>But if you have a long drive or trip coming up, buckle up.</p>
			<ul class="links">
				<li><a href="https://daringfireball.net/thetalkshow/2025/07/31/ep-428">#428: Michigan-Starred Dining</a></li>
			</ul>
			<hr>
			<p>If you like this, you can <a class="button donate" href="https://donate.stripe.com/eVag0g952cl90aQ9AA">make a one-time donation</a>, <a href="https://patreon.com/LouieMantia">donate monthly</a>, or buy something from my <a class="button" href="https://lmnt.me/shop/">shop</a>.</p>
		]]></description>
	</item>

	<item>
		<title>Tap Tap Revolution</title>
		<pubDate>Fri, 25 Jul 2025 12:15:00 +0900</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">CD7A033E-A655-42A8-8D61-6A35BFB9EB8C</guid>
		<link>https://lmnt.me/blog/tap-tap-revolution.html</link>
		<dc:creator>Louie Mantia</dc:creator>
		<description><![CDATA[
			<p>Here’s a third recent project to round out this little mini series of “What has Louie been up to?”</p>
			<p><em>Tap Tap Revolution</em>. Yeah.</p>
			<figure>
				<img src="https://lmnt.me/files/images/tap-tap-revolution.webp">
				<figcaption>Three comps of a theoretical new version of <em>Tap Tap Revolution</em>: its menu, a transition to gameplay, and its iconic red-green-blue tracks.</figcaption>
			</figure>
			<p>Blast from the past, right? My old boss, Bart Decrem, came to me a little while ago with a wild proposition. What if they remade <em>Tap Tap Revenge</em> today? The original App Store hit. What would it look like? Would it be <em>Tap Tap Revolution</em>, its original jailbreak-era name?</p>
			<p>What a fun thought. I took it in earnest and designed what I think it would look like today, taking it back to the roots of the product, incorporating modern design sensibilities <small>(and also reflections of my own growth as a designer)</small>.</p>
			<p>A lot has changed since 2008. Our phones got taller, bigger in general. The height of the tapping area along the bottom would probably have to be taller to compensate for the size and weight of phones today. But wouldn’t it be super cool if it was all pulled off really well?</p>
			<p>I want to play a new version of the app that made the iPod touch <a href="https://lmnt.me/blog/tapulous.html">the funnest iPod ever</a>.</p>
			<hr>
			<p>If you like this, you can <a class="button donate" href="https://donate.stripe.com/eVag0g952cl90aQ9AA">make a one-time donation</a>, <a href="https://patreon.com/LouieMantia">donate monthly</a>, or buy something from my <a class="button" href="https://lmnt.me/shop/">shop</a>.</p>
		]]></description>
